4. Multiple linear regression

Multiple linear regression in R follows the same syntax we’ve been using so far:

lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3..., data = df_name)

Let’s try this model a couple of different ways:

  1. Use all available variables (saturated model)
  2. Use only SqFt as a predictor for “home size” generally (omit Bathrooms and Bedrooms), and omit PricePerSqFt (since it’s derived from two other existing variables in the model)

Use summary() to view the model output and statistics.

(Cannot evaluate residuals without making the model first)

# a. Saturated model: 

homes_lm1 <- lm(Price ~ City + Bedrooms + Bathrooms + SqFt + PricePerSqFt + Status, data = homes_sub)

homes_lm1

##       StatusShort Sale

# Finds a model that determines price in relation to these variables

# PricePerSqFt is directly derived from the price (price column divided by square foot column) - so no error in this being associated by price outcome variable. So there is no uncertainty related to the relationship between the two (no sampling error or vairation) - So using this variable to find price is not a random variable being measured (in a biased way this will improve model fit because it is based on a calculation based on outcome variable you are trying to predict)

# List of coefficients is the model equation

# Looking at the linear model coefficients: If everything about two houses is otherwise exactly the same, if you increase the number of bedrooms by 1, the house price will go down by $30,792.8 .... something is going on with our variables we've selected because conceptually this doesn't make sense!

# When we have categorical variables we are comparing it to a reference level -- our reference level is foreclosure -- this says that regular sale goes down by $19792 commpared to floreclosure sale

# For every one square foot increase, I would expect the average housing price to go up by $245.93 # If we buy a house for regular sale we would expect to pay $209998 more than foreclosure sale
# Always talking about outputs with respect to reference level (foreclosure sale and Arroyo Grande)
# Short sale is only $2282 more than foreclosure sale (not that significant)
# Will always be error -- should ask "what are things that could improve this model?"
# This model overall is highly significant according to p-value in F-statistic line 
# Multiple and adjusted R square - adjusted accounts for the fact that model fit will go up just with more variables so will be a little lower
# Multiple R-squared- 53% fit to the regression line (the model explains 53% of the variability of the response data around the mean)
# There are many other variables that would help improve model fit (i.e. school district, exact location, age, etc.)

Wait…but what if I wanted everything to be with respect to a Regular sale status? Then I need to change my factor levels. We’ve done this before, here we’ll use a different function (fct_relevel) from forcats package in the tidyverse.

# a. Set Status to class 'factor'

### Status is still defined by R as a character so we need to coerce it into a factor

homes_sub$Status <- factor (homes_sub$Status) # Not changing any of the information in the column, just changing how R reads it, so it's OK not to use mutate



# b. Check to ensure it's a factor now
## Use class()


# c. Check levels:
## Use levels()

# d. Reassign reference level of "Status" to "Regular":
## fct_relevel() function in forcats

homes_sub$Status <- fct_relevel(homes_sub$Status, "Regular") # Takes this level, puts it first, and then everything else will be alphabetical afterwards, or you can continue listing them which will order all levels

5. Model diagnostics

Remember, since we’re concerned about residuals (distance that actual observations exist from model predictions), we can only evaluate some assumptions after running the regression.

Then we can evaluate model diagnostics using the plot() function:

# a. Model diagnostics:

plot(homes_lm3)

6. Model comparison by Akaike Information Criterion

The AIC is a quantitative metric for model “optimization” that balances complexity with model fit. The best models are the ones that fit the data as well as possible, as simply as possible. Recall: lower AIC value indicates a more optimal balance - BUT STATISTICS IS NO SUBSTITUTE FOR JUDGEMENT!!!

# a. AIC values for each model

## Absolute values mean nothing, it's just a comparative tool!

full_aic <- AIC (homes_lm1)
final_aic <- AIC (homes_lm3)


# Answer: which would you pick? 

## If I'm using this as a final decision making tool as a predictor of price, and only looked at AIC, I would pick the first one! Because it's lower ... but should NOT be used as a final decision making tool.

8. Making predictions

Using your final selected model, predict the housing price for a range of home sizes, sale status, and city.

The predict() function uses the following syntax:

  predict(model_name, newdata = new_data_name)

Defaults are to exclude the prediction SE and mean confidence interval - if you want to include, use arguments

  se.fit = TRUE
  interval = "confidence" 
  interval = "prediction"

First, you need to create a new data frame of values that contain ALL NECESSARY VARIABLES with the same variable names AND level strings.

# First, make a new data frame

# Note that the df_new created below has the SAME variable names and level strings as the original model data (otherwise R won't know how to use it...)
# Work through this on your own to figure out what it actually does:

                                  "Santa Maria-Orcutt",
                                  "Atascadero",
                                  "Arroyo Grande"), 
                                each = 60), 
                     SqFt = rep(seq(from = 500,
                                    to = 3500, 
                                    length = 20), 
                                times = 12),
